The '''Ford Model F''' is an [[automobile]] produced by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]. It was a development of the [[Ford Model A (1903)|Model A]] and [[Ford Model C|Model C]], but was larger, more modern, and more luxurious.  Production started in 1905 and ended in 1906 after about 1,000 were made. It was built at the [[Ford Piquette Avenue Plant]].  It was a four-seater [[Phaeton body|phaeton]] with [[running board]]s and a side-entrance [[tonneau]] standard.  It was priced from {{USD|1,000|1906}}<ref name="newspaper">Ford Motor Company Newspaper Advertisement from 1905. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ford-Model-F-and-Doctors-Car.jpg</ref> to {{USD|1,200|1905}};<ref name="oldcarbrochure"/> by contrast, the [[Colt Runabout Company|Colt Runabout]] was $1,500,<ref>Clymer, p.63.</ref> the [[Fal-Car|FAL]] was $1,750,<ref name="Clymer, p.104">Clymer, p.104.</ref> the [[Cole (car company)|Cole 30]] $1,500,<ref name="Clymer, p.104"/> the [[Enger Motor Car Company|Enger 40]] $2,000,<ref name="Clymer, p.104"/> and the [[Lozier]] Light Six Metropolitan $3,250.<ref>Clymer, p.111.</ref> All had green bodies.<ref name="Kimes 1996"/>

