{{Infobox automobile | image = Henry Ford Museum August 2012 91 (1905 Ford Model B).jpg | name = Ford Model B | manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | production = 1904&ndash;1906 | predecessor = [[Ford Model A (1903-1904)|Ford Model A]] | successor = [[Ford Model K]] | class = Upscale | platform = | body_style = 2-row 4-passenger [[touring car]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=standard catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref> | engine = 283.5CID 24hp [[Straight-4]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=standard catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref> | transmission = 2-speed [[Epicyclic gearing|planetary]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=standard catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref> | wheelbase = 92&nbsp;in (2337&nbsp;mm) | length = | width = | height = | weight = 1700lbs.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=standard catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref> | aka = | related = Cadillac 8 1/2 {{CN|date=December 2016}} | designer = [[Henry Ford]] }}
The '''Ford Model B''' is an upscale [[touring car]] (with polished wood and brass trim) that was introduced in 1904 by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]. It was built at the [[Ford Piquette Avenue Plant]]. It was Ford's first car to use the [[Front-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|front-engine layout]], with a large 24&nbsp;hp 4-cylinder engine positioned at the front behind a conventional radiator. The smaller [[Ford Model A (1903-1904)|Model A]]-derived [[Ford Model C|Model C]] positioned its flat 2-cylinder motor under the seat.
[[File:1904 Ford Model B Touring.jpg|thumb|1904 Ford Model B Touring]] Priced at $2000<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=standard catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|2000|1904|r=-3}} today), the Model B was a high end car. Produced for three years, sales were predictably slower than the Model C which was priced at 1/3 the cost. The Model B was replaced by the derivative [[Ford Model K|Model K]] in 1906.
