{{Infobox automobile | image = 1907 Ford Model K Tourer (Warbirds & Wheels museum).jpg | name = Ford Model K | manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] | production = 1906&ndash;1908 | predecessor = [[Ford Model B (1904)|Ford Model B]] | successor = | class = Upscale | platform = | body_style = 2-row [[touring car]] | engine = 405CID cast iron block 40hp [[Straight-6]]<ref name=Kimes>{{cite book|last=Kimes|first=Beverly|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1805-1942|year=1996|publisher=Krause Publications|isbn=0-87341-428-4}}</ref><ref name=brochure>{{cite web|title=1906 Ford Advance Brochure|url=http://www.oldcarbrochures.com/static/NA/Ford/1906_Ford/1906_Ford_%20Advance_Brochure/1906%20Ford%203.html|publisher=The Old Car Manual Project|accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref> | transmission = planetary 2-speed manual<ref name=brochure/> | wheelbase = {{convert|114|in|cm|0|abbr=on}} | length = | width = | height = | weight = {{convert|2400|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=brochure/> | aka = | related = | designer = [[Henry Ford]] }} The '''Ford Model K''' is an upscale [[automobile]] that was produced by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]. It was introduced in 1906 and replaced the earlier [[Ford Model B (1904)|Model B]]. It was built at the [[Ford Piquette Avenue Plant]]. The model K was aimed at the top end of the market and featured an [[inline-6]] (the only Ford six until [[1941 Ford|1941]]) giving 40&nbsp;hp (30&nbsp;kW). The wheelbase was 120 in (2896&nbsp;mm) and could be ordered either as a touring or roadster model.
Contrary to popular folklore, the Model K was a good seller for Ford Motor Company. In 1906, the first year it was offered, the Model K produced over 85 percent of Ford Motor Company's new car profit (1906 Ford Motor Company internal audit records).
[[File:1907 Ford Model K 6-40 Roadster.jpg|thumb|1907 Ford Model K 6-40 Roadster]] In 1907, the second sales year of the Model K, almost 500 examples were sold, making it the best-selling six-cylinder model in the world.
As period journals reported, Ford Motor Company went in another direction, moving to one chassis, a mid-priced car, the [[Model T]], leaving the multi-line business model used by most auto makers of the period. However, sales and profits from the Model K helped Ford Motor Company become the largest automaker in number of sales in 1907, and along with the Model N, was the only Ford model sold through three model years (1906–1908) prior to the advent of the Model T.
