{{Distinguish|text=the [[Citicar]] variant called Comuta-Car}} {{Infobox automobile | name = Ford Comuta | image = | manufacturer = [[Ford]] | aka = | production = | model_years = | assembly = | predecessor = | successor = | class = [[Microcar]] | body_style = | layout = | platform = | engine = | transmission = | wheelbase = | length = | width = | height = | weight = | related = | designer = | sp = us }}
The '''Ford Comuta''' was an experimental [[electric vehicle]] designed by [[Ford]] in the 1960s. The vehicle was powered by four 12-[[volt]] 85-Ah [[lead batteries]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/images/ManualSSPL/10221430.aspx | title=Ford Comuta electric car, 1967 | author=<!--Not stated--> | date=2010 | publisher=Science Museum | location=London | access-date={{date|June 6, 2017|mdy}} | url-status=dead | archive-date={{date|February 4, 2010|mdy}} | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204203814/http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/images/ManualSSPL/10221430.aspx }}</ref>
When it was fully charged, the car had a range of {{convert|60|km|mi}} at a speed of {{convert|40|km/h|mph}}, and was capable of a maximum speed of {{convert|60|km/h|mph}}. Only a handful Comutas were produced, as the vehicle was an experiment.<ref>{{cite news | last=Stevens | first=Tim | date={{date|July 9, 2010|mdy}} | title=Looking back at Ford's EV past, forward to the 2012 Focus Electric and a 2013 plug-in hybrid | url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/09/07/looking-fords-ev-past-and-forward-to-the-2012-focus-electric-a/ | url-status=live | work=Endgadget | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909061625/https://www.engadget.com/2010/09/07/looking-fords-ev-past-and-forward-to-the-2012-focus-electric-a/ | archive-date={{date|September 7, 2010|mdy}} | access-date={{date|June 23, 2017|mdy}} }}</ref>
