The '''Ford Fusion''' is a four-door, five-passenger [[mid-size car|mid-size sedan]] manufactured and marketed by the [[Ford Motor Company]]. Introduced for the 2006 model year, two generations of the Fusion have been produced in gasoline, gas/electric hybrid, and gas/plug-in electric hybrid variants. The Fusion is manufactured at Ford's [[Hermosillo Stamping and Assembly]] plant in [[Sonora, Mexico]], alongside its [[badge engineering|rebadged variant]] the [[Lincoln MKZ]], and formerly the [[Mercury Milan]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/05_24/b3937071_mz058.htm |title=Business Week June 13, 2005 |work=[[Business Week]] |date=June 13, 2005 |accessdate=January 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904043512/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/05_24/b3937071_mz058.htm |archivedate=September 4, 2011 }}</ref> both of which share its [[Ford CD3 platform|CD3]] platform. Ford announced in April 2018 that it would discontinue the Fusion within a few years.<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2018/04/26/ford-taurus-fiesta-fusion/553539002/</ref>

Production on the first Fusions began on August 1, 2005.<ref name=Wards06>{{cite book |title= Ward's Automotive Yearbook 2006 |publisher=Ward's Communications, Inc |editor=Binder, Alan K. |year=2006 |page=102}}</ref> The Fusion replaced the [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo]] for the Latin American markets—except in Argentina (where the current European Mondeo is available) and in the United States and Canada (where it superseded the then mid-size Taurus and the compact [[Ford Contour|Contour]]). The Fusion is positioned between the compact [[Ford Focus (North America)|Ford Focus]] and the full-size [[Ford Taurus]].<ref name="EPA FuelEconomy.gov">{{cite web|url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/bymanu.htm |title=Environmental Protection Agency Fuel Economy |department= FuelEconomy.com | publisher= US Department of Energy |accessdate= November 18, 2007}}</ref> In the [[Middle East]], this model is sold alongside the [[Ford Mondeo|Mondeo]]. Versions sold there are available only with the 2.5-liter engine. Unlike in the United States, Canada, and Latin America, no V6 engine is available in that region.<ref name="DriveArabia">{{cite web|url=http://www.drivearabia.com/ultimatecarbuyerguide/usedcarspage2.php/18|title=Ultimate Car Buyer Guide|work=DriveArabia.com|accessdate=June 1, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923055258/http://drivearabia.com/ultimatecarbuyerguide/usedcarspage2.php/18|archivedate=September 23, 2010}}</ref>  The same is true in South Korea, where only the 2.5-liter engines (including those for the hybrid model) are available as of the 2012 model year.

The third generation line-up includes a gasoline engine option, an [[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost engine]] option, a next-generation hybrid model, and a [[plug-in hybrid]] version, the [[Ford Fusion Energi]], making the Ford Fusion the first production sedan to offer these four options. Sales of the gasoline-powered and hybrid versions began in the U.S. in October 2012 under the 2013 model. Sales in Europe and Asia, as Ford Mondeo, are expected to begin in 2015, along with South Africa, where the Fusion name will be used.<ref>[http://www.carmag.co.za/news/new-models/2015-ford-fusion-rings-the-changes/ 2015 FORD FUSION RINGS THE CHANGES], ''CAR'', July 15, 2014</ref> Deliveries of the Fusion Energi began in the U.S. in February 2013. The entire 2013 Ford Fusion line-up was awarded with the 2013 [[Green Car of the Year]] at the [[Los Angeles Auto Show#2012|2012 Los Angeles Auto Show]]. In 2019, [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] Fusion was the 7th best selling car in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/12/15/tesla-model-3-9th-best-selling-car-in-usa/|title=Tesla Model 3 = 9th Best Selling Car In USA|date=2019-12-16|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>

==First generation (2006–2012)==

{{Infobox automobile
