====Safety ratings====
The Ford Fusion line-up was included in the [[Insurance Institute for Highway Safety]] 2010 "Top Safety Picks" rating for the [[Mid-size car|mid-size]] category.<ref name="IIHS2010">{{cite web|url=http://www.iihs.org/ratings/default.aspx|title=TOP SAFETY PICKs 2010|publisher=[[Insurance Institute for Highway Safety]]|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name="ConsumerR10">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.consumerreports.org/cars/2010/06/iihs-chooses-9-more-top-safety-picks.html|title=IIHS chooses 9 more Top Safety Picks|publisher=[[Consumer Reports]]|date=June 9, 2010|accessdate=June 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612152425/http://blogs.consumerreports.org/cars/2010/06/iihs-chooses-9-more-top-safety-picks.html|archivedate=June 12, 2010}}</ref> Due to the fact that [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] modified and strengthened the roof structure of the Flex, Fusion, and MKT vehicles, these 2010 ratings apply only to [[Lincoln MKZ]]s, [[Mercury Milan]] and Fusions built after April 2010.<ref name=IIHS2010/>

====Safety concerns====
In June 2010, it was reported that [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] was investigating into floormat-related [[Sudden unintended acceleration|unintended acceleration]] in 2010 Ford Fusion and Mercury Milan. According to NHTSA's estimate, as many as 249,301 cars could be affected.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/06/ford-fusion-faces-probe-over-gas-pedal-getting-caught-under-floor-mat/1 |title=Ford Fusion faces probe over gas pedal getting caught under floor mat |date=June 1, 2010 |work=USA Today |accessdate=June 2, 2010 }}</ref>

On May 28, 2010, the NHTSA issued a statement that the stacking of all-weather floor mats from any manufacturer on top of the factory floor mat could cause accelerator entrapment. In their press release they stated the following: "NHTSA is urging drivers of 2010 Fusions to make sure they do not stack the rubber “All Weather” floor mat on top of the secured carpeted floor mat. Further, drivers are reminded to ensure that any driver-side floor mats (whether they are the carpeted floor mat or all weather floor mat) are properly installed and restrained by the retention hooks on the floorboard. Depending on vehicle and floor mat design, it is possible for unsecured floor mats to interfere with accelerator or brake pedals in a wide range of vehicles. Therefore, NHTSA reminds all drivers of all makes and models to check the driver-side floor mats for secure installation and to follow all manufacturer instructions for installing the mats."<ref>{{cite press release| title= Consumer Advisory: Owners of MY 2010 Ford Fusion and Mercury Milan Warned of Possible Stuck Accelerator Pedals |url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/About+NHTSA/Press+Releases/2010/ci.Consumer+Advisory:+Owners+of+MY+2010+Ford+Fusion+and+Mercury+Milan+Warned+of+Possible+Stuck+Accelerator+Pedals.print | date= May 28, 2010 | publisher= National Highway Traffic Safety Administration | first= Julia |last= Piscitelli | accessdate= April 19, 2013}}</ref>

On October 2, 2014, the NHTSA's Office of Defects Investigation opened an investigation into the Electronic Power Assisted Steering (EPAS) subsystem used in Ford Fusions, Lincoln MKZs, and Mercury Milans with model years between 2010 and 2012. The investigation was opened in response to over 500 complaints where motorists reported the sudden loss of power steering while driving. An estimated 938,000 vehicles are included in the investigation. The investigation is ongoing.<ref>{{cite web|title=ODI Resume|url=http://www-odi.nhtsa.dot.gov/acms/cs/jaxrs/download/doc/UCM463722/INOA-PE14030-2570.PDF|publisher=National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|accessdate=April 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411084455/http://www-odi.nhtsa.dot.gov/acms/cs/jaxrs/download/doc/UCM463722/INOA-PE14030-2570.PDF|archive-date=April 11, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On May 27, 2015, Ford issued a recall for 2011-2012 Ford Fusions, Mercury Milans, and Lincoln MKZ's made in Mexico, along with 2011-2013 Ford Taurus, Ford Flex, Lincoln MKS and Lincoln MKT's built in Chicago or Oakville. The repair involves a software update and/or steering replacement due to a malfunctioning sensor.<ref>{{cite press release|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Ford Issues Two Safety Recalls in North America|url=https://media.ford.com/content/fordmedia/fna/us/en/news/2015/05/27/ford-issues-two-safety-recalls-in-north-america-.html|publisher=[[Ford Motor Company]]|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=May 30, 2015}}</ref>

===Hybrid electric version===
{{main|Ford Fusion Hybrid}}
[[File:Ford Fusion Hybrid digital panels.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Fusion Hybrid]] has digital panels to track [[eco driving]] (top), and current hybrid drive propulsion (bottom).]]
The 2010 [[Ford Fusion Hybrid]] is a [[hybrid electric vehicle|gasoline-electric hybrid]] powered version of the [[Mid-size car|mid-size]] Fusion sedan launched to the U.S. market in March 2009, with an initial sale price of US$27,270.<ref name=GreenCar0409>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2009/04/us-hybrid-sales-in-march-2009-down-44-yearonyear-monthly-new-vehicle-market-share-of-25.html#more|title=US Hybrid Sales in March 2009 Down 44% Year-on-Year; Monthly New Vehicle Market Share of 2.5%|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]] |date=April 3, 2009|accessdate=June 6, 2009}}</ref> [[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] ratings for the Ford Fusion Hybrid are 41 mpg city and 36 mpg highway. In city driving a full tank delivers 700 miles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://autos.nytimes.com/2010/Ford/Fusion/245/10005/308905/NCTD/researchReviews.aspx|title=2010 Ford Fusion 4dr Sdn S FWD|work=The New York Times|first=Ted|last=West|accessdate=June 6, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720073641/http://autos.nytimes.com/2010/Ford/Fusion/245/10005/308905/NCTD/researchReviews.aspx|archive-date=July 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2009 editors of [[Kelley Blue Book]] named the 2010 Ford Fusion Hybrid to its 2009 list of "Top 10 Green Cars".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docKey=600-200904201035PR_NEWS_USPR_____DE01437-22ABH29OJIPNI1BB6OJIDB417Q&provider=PR%20Newswire&docDate=April%2020%2C%202009&press_symbol=US%3BF&scp=14&sq=Ford%20Fusion%20Hybrid&st=cse|title=Two Ford Vehicles Make KBB's Top 10 Green Cars List|work=New York Times |date=April 22, 2009|accessdate=June 6, 2009}}</ref>

The Fusion Hybrid qualified for a [[hybrid tax credit]] of US$3,400 prior to March 31, 2009. The credit dropped to US$1,700 if purchased by September 30, 2009, and to US$850 if purchased by March 31, 2010. This credit phased out on April 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.ford.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=29778|title=2010 Fusion and 2009 Escape Hybrids Provide Buyers Top Tax Credits|publisher=[[Ford Motor Company]]|date=January 28, 2009|accessdate=June 6, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818015022/http://media.ford.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=29778|archivedate=August 18, 2009}}</ref>

This model gets better EPA-estimated fuel economy than the [[Toyota Camry Hybrid]], the [[Nissan Altima Hybrid]], and the [[Chevrolet Malibu Hybrid]], viewed as its competitors in the mid-size ''[[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]'' segment.

''[[Consumer Reports]]'' in its December 6, 2012 publication found that the Ford Fusion Hybrid and Ford C-Max Hybrid's tested fuel economy was 20% (8 MPG) short of Ford's EPA mileage claims. After many reports from owners and media of the Ford Fusion Hybrid getting less than the stated 47 MPG city/47 MPG highway/47 MPG combined, a class action lawsuit was brought against Ford on December 26, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://green.autoblog.com/2012/12/26/ford-dealt-class-action-lawsuit-over-c-max-fusion-hybrid-mileag/ |title=Ford dealt class-action lawsuit over C-Max, Fusion hybrid mileage claims | first= Sebastian |last= Blanco | work= Autoblog | date= December 26, 2012 | accessdate= April 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://mpgfraud.com/pdf/Pitkin-FILED-COMPLAINT.pdf |publisher= MPGFraud.com | title= Class Action Complaint | work=Pitkin v. Ford Motor Company | location=United States District Court, Eastern District of California | first1= Richard D. |last1= McCune |first2=Elaine S. |last2= Kusel |first3= Jae (Eddie) K. |last3= Kim| date= December 7, 2012| accessdate= April 19, 2013}}</ref> Consumer Reports reviewed several other vehicle makes and models and found the Fusion Hybrid from Ford were the worst under-performers compared to EPA fuel efficiency ratings in real world usage compared to 16 others including hybrids.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2012/12/video-tests-show-2013-ford-fusion-c-max-hybrids-dont-live-up-to-47-mpg-claims.html | title= Tests show Ford Fusion, C-Max hybrids don't live up to 47-mpg claims | work= [[Consumer Reports]] | publisher= [[Consumers Union]] | date= December 6, 2012 | accessdate= April 19, 2013 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130414134501/http://news.consumerreports.org/cars/2012/12/video-tests-show-2013-ford-fusion-c-max-hybrids-dont-live-up-to-47-mpg-claims.html | archive-date= April 14, 2013 | url-status= dead }}</ref>
{{clear}}

