2017-2020 Ford introduced a revised 2.0 engine with a twin scroll turbocharger producing 245hp and 275lbft with 1 mpg overall increase in fuel economy

===Hybrid===
The new 2013 line-up also includes a next-generation hybrid version, and a [[plug-in hybrid]] version, the [[Ford Fusion Energi]]. The Ford Fusion became the first production sedan to offer these three options.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ford.com/cars/fusion/2013/?searchid=|title=2013 Fusion|publisher=Ford Motor Company|accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> Sales of the gasoline-powered and hybrid version began in the US in October 2012.<ref name="Oct12">{{cite web| url= http://media.ford.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=37314| title= Ford C-MAX Hybrid Outsells Toyota Prius v in First Full Sales Month, Helps Ford Set Hybrid, Small Vehicle Sales Records| publisher= Ford Motor Company| date= November 2, 2012| accessdate= November 18, 2012| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121104190005/http://media.ford.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=37314| archivedate= November 4, 2012}}</ref> Sales in Europe and Asia, as Ford Mondeo, are expected to begin in 2013.<ref name="NYT010912">{{cite news| url= http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/09/ford-adds-plug-in-hybrid-to-fusion-arsenal/ |title=Ford Adds Plug-In Hybrid to Fusion Arsenal| first= Christopher | last= Jensen|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Deliveries of the Fusion Energi began the U.S. in February 2013.<ref name="EnergiDelivery01">{{cite news |url=http://pricinginsider.carsdirect.com/2013/02/27/2013-ford-fusion-energi-fuel-economy-pricing-and-release-date/ |title=2013 Ford Fusion Energi: Fuel Economy, Pricing and Release Date |first=Jesse |last=Sears |publisher=Cars Direct |date=February 27, 2013 |accessdate=March 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305135302/http://pricinginsider.carsdirect.com/2013/02/27/2013-ford-fusion-energi-fuel-economy-pricing-and-release-date/ |archivedate=March 5, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="EnergiDelivery02">{{cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/february-2013-plug-in-electric-vehicle-sales-report-card/ |title=February 2013 Plug-In Electric Vehicle Sales Report Card |first=Jay |last=Cole |publisher=Inside EVs |date=March 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304012451/http://insideevs.com/february-2013-plug-in-electric-vehicle-sales-report-card/ |archivedate=March 4, 2013 }}</ref> Sales of the Mondeo line-up, including the hybrid model, began in Germany in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kfz-betrieb.vogel.de/neuwagen/handel/articles/455328/?cmp=nl-125|title=First Order für den neuen Ford Mondeo|language=German|trans-title=First Order for the new Ford Mondeo|author=Staff|work=KFZ-betrieb |date=August 8, 2014|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

For the [[Ford Mondeo Hybrid|second generation Fusion Hybrid]] the [[nickel-metal hydride battery|nickel-metal hydride batteries]] used in the hybrid first generation were replaced with [[lithium-ion batteries]].<ref name=NYT010912/>  The 2013 model year is more fuel efficient than its predecessor, with a [[US Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) rating of {{convert|47|mpgus|abbr=on}} with the same rating for combined/city/highway cycles. This rating is also the same Ford achieved for the 2013 [[Ford C-Max Hybrid]], as both hybrids share the same engine and drivetrain. These ratings allowed the 2013 Fusion Hybrid to outperform the 2012 [[Toyota Camry Hybrid]] LE by 4&nbsp;mpg‑US (0,5&nbsp;L/100&nbsp;km; 4.8&nbsp;mpg‑imp) city and 8&nbsp;mpg‑US (1&nbsp;L/100&nbsp;km; 9.6&nbsp;mpg‑imp) highway, and to become the most efficient midsize hybrid sedan in the U.S. as of September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1079221_2013-ford-fusion-hybrid-gets-epa-approved-47mpg-all-round|title=2013 Ford Fusion Hybrid Gets EPA-Approved 47MPG All-Round|first= Nikki|last= Gordon-Bloomfield|publisher=Green Car Reports| date= September 18, 2012 |accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref> The Duratec 2.5, and EcoBoost 1.5, 1.6 and 2.0 are sourced from [[Chihuahua, Chihuahua|Chihuahua, Mexico]]; [[Craiova, Romania]]; [[Bridgend, Wales]]; and [[Valencia, Spain]] respectively. The 6F and HF35 automatic transmissions are sourced from Ford's Van Dyke Transmission Plant in [[Sterling Heights, Michigan]], while the B6 manual is produced at the GETRAG FORD Transmissions GmbH facility in [[Halewood, United Kingdom]].

===2017 facelift===
Ford updated the Fusion for the 2017 model year. The facelifted version was first unveiled at the [[North American International Auto Show#2016|2016 North American International Auto Show]] on January 11, 2016.
[[File:Ford Fusion SE 2.0 EcoBoost 2017 (34956635573).jpg|thumb|right|2017 facelift]]
All Fusions received new packages, new front and rear end styling, a new rotary-controlled automatic transmission, and two new trim levels of the gasoline-powered Fusion: the high-performance '''Sport''', which marks the first time that a [[V6]] engine has been installed into a second-generation Fusion, and the '''Platinum''', which adds more luxury features onto the previously top-of-the-line Titanium trim level (the Platinum is also available for both the Fusion Hybrid and Fusion Energi models). Also new for 2017 on most Fusion models is Ford's new SYNC 3 infotainment system with [[Android Auto]] and [[Apple CarPlay]] compatibility, which replaces the [[MyFord Touch]] infotainment system that was offered on the 2016 Fusion.

Pricing starts at $22,120 for a base gas-powered Fusion S model with the 2.5 L [[Duratec]] I4 engine, and tops out at $39,120 for a top-of-the-line Fusion Energi Platinum model with a 2.0 L I4 engine and an Atkinson Cycle electric motor with EV Mode.

===2019 facelift===
Ford again updated the Fusion for the 2019 model year.  This version debuted at the [[New York International Auto Show#2018|2018 New York International Auto Show]], set to go on sale in late summer 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2018/03/20/2019-ford-fusion-updates/|title=2019 Ford Fusion has more standard features and fresh styling|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://media.ford.com/content/fordmedia/fna/us/en/news/2018/03/20/sleeker-smarter-2019-ford-fusion.html|title=Sleeker, Smarter 2019 Fusion Is First Ford with Standard Ford Co-Pilot360 Driver-Assist Technology, Greater Plug-In Hybrid Range - Ford Media Center|website=media.ford.com}}</ref>
[[File:2019 Ford Fusion Hybrid SE, Blue, front left.jpg|thumb|2019 facelift]]
The 2019 Fusion adds Ford's "Co-Pilot 360" safety suite as standard on all models.  It includes automatic emergency braking, lane-keeping assist, blind-spot and rear-cross-traffic warning systems, automatic highbeams, and automatic wipers.

The new models have updated front and rear styling.  The 1.5 L EcoBoost engine is now standard on SE and higher models, except for the '''V6 Sport''', formerly known as Sport.  The '''SEL''' replaces the SE Luxury Package, and the Platinum is dropped, moving the Titanium up-level.  The Hybrid is no longer available in base S trim, and the Energi is available only in Titanium trim.  The Energi model's battery range will increase from 22 miles to 25 miles, and the battery may take less space in the trunk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1115817_2019-ford-fusion-energi-plug-in-hybrid-gets-25-miles-from-revised-battery|title=2019 Ford Fusion Energi plug-in hybrid gets 25 miles from revised battery|publisher=}}</ref>

===2020 changes===

For the 2020 [[model year]], the Fusion lineup has been condensed. There are now four gasoline-only Fusion models: S, SE, SEL, and Titanium, two Fusion Hybrid models (SE and Titanium), and only one Fusion Energi Plug-In Hybrid ([[PHEV]]) model: the Titanium. The Sport, Hybrid S, and Energi SE trims have all been discontinued for 2020. All trim levels offer a higher level of standard equipment, as well as fewer options. The S trim level is powered by a 2.5L DuraTec inline four-cylinder (I4) naturally-aspirated gasoline engine. SE and SEL trims are powered by the 1.5L [[EcoBoost]] turbocharged I4 gasoline engine, and the Titanium trim level is powered by the 2.0L [[EcoBoost]] turbocharged I4 gasoline engine. All Fusion Hybrid and Fusion Energi models are powered by an [[Atkinson cycle]] naturally-aspirated 2.0L I4 gasoline engine with an electric motor, as well as a [[Continuously Variable Transmission]] (CVT). Gasoline-only Fusion models use a six-speed automatic transmission. All Fusion Hybrid and Fusion Energi models are exclusively offered with [[front wheel drive]] (FWD), while select gasoline-only Fusion models are offered with [[all wheel drive]]. 

All trim levels offer Ford's SYNC 3 touchscreen infotainment system with [[Apple CarPlay]] and [[Android Auto]] [[smartphone]] integration and [[SiriusXM]] [[Satellite Radio]] and Travel Link service, GPS navigation, and the FordPass Connect [[4G]] [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]] mobile [[Wi-Fi]] hotspot as standard equipment, except for the base S, where it is available as part of the [[Ford]] CoPilot360+ Package. All models feature Ford's CoPilot360 driver assistance system, with most models also offering the Ford CoPilot360+ system. S and SE trims receive cloth seating surfaces, while SEL and Hybrid SE models receive "Active-X" leatherette-trimmed seating surfaces, and Titanium, Hybrid Titanium, and Energi Titanium receive leather-trimmed seating surfaces.

The Sport and its 2.7L twin-turbocharged [[EcoBoost]] V6 gasoline engine have been discontinued for the 2020 [[model year]].

===Safety and recall===
In 2012, Ford recalled about 90,000 2013 Ford Escape and Fusion in the U.S. and Canada with 1.6-liter engines that may overheat and cause fires after 13 reports of fire were reported to Ford.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ford recalls 2013 Escape, Fusion: Potential fires in 89,000 cars with 1.6-liter engine|url=http://autoweek.com/article/car-news/ford-recalls-2013-escape-fusion-potential-fires-89000-cars-16-liter-engine|website=Autoweek|accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref>

In 2017, Ford recalled 2013-2014 Ford Fusion with 1.6 ecoboost engines because of a risk of engine fires caused by a “lack of coolant circulation”. The recall partly contributed to a charge of US$300 million by Ford.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=Jim|title=Ford recalls 230,000 cars over potential engine fires|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/ford/2017/03/29/ford-recall/99771750/|accessdate=April 1, 2017|work=The Detroit News|date=March 29, 2017}}</ref>

In 2018, Ford recalled 2013-15 Ford Fusion with 1.6-liter Sigma GTDI engines and B6 manual transmissions, due to potential risk of the steering wheel becoming loose.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ford recalls nearly 1.4 million cars, steering wheel can come loose|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/14/ford-recalls-nearly-1-point-4-million-cars-steering-wheel-can-come-loose.html}}</ref>

On May 15, 2019, Ford recalled about 270,000 2013-16 Ford Fusion with the 2.5L engine and automatic transmission due to the possibility that a bushing that holds the transmission lever safety cable in place could detach from the cable, which could potentially lead to the transmission lever safety cable becoming detached from the bushing, and allowing the transmission to not remain in 'Park', even if 'Park' is selected. If the transmission shift lever safety cable becomes loose, the vehicle will falsely register that the transmission is in 'Park', and will not show a warning message or sound a warning chime upon removal of the ignition key, and could also pose a rollaway risk. <ref>https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/ford/2019/05/15/ford-recall-ranger-fusion-transmission/3677845002/</ref>

==Future==
Ford initially planned to discontinue the Fusion along with its other sedans in North America in the next few years, as part of a plan to focus more on SUVs and trucks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/04/26/605971051/ford-to-phase-out-traditional-ford-sedans-such-as-fusion-and-taurus-in-the-u-s|title=Ford To Phase Out 'Traditional Ford Sedans' Such As Fusion And Taurus In The U.S.|last=Chappell|first=Bill|date=April 26, 2018|work=National Public Radio|access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref> The Fusion is expected to be the last sedan sold by Ford ([[Lincoln Motor Company|Lincoln]] notwithstanding), with the [[Ford Taurus (sixth generation)|Ford Taurus]] and [[Ford Fiesta]] being dropped in North America in early 2019;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autoweek.com/article/rumormill/ford-fusion-may-live|title=The Ford Fusion may live on|publisher=}}</ref> the Fusion will also be the last traditional car aside from the [[Ford Mustang]] offered by the Ford division.

However, a report by [[Bloomberg News]] in July 2018, citing an unnamed Ford source, is stating that Ford is reconsidering dropping the Fusion name due to strong [[brand equity]] in the name as well as dealer protests. While the sedan will still be dropped, the reports now state that the Fusion will live on as a [[Subaru Outback]]-like [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover wagon]] likely called the Fusion Active and based on the current Fusion's [[Ford CD4 platform]]. The Fusion's transformation would be similar to that of the [[Buick Regal]], which in 2018 went from being a sedan to a wagon and [[fastback]]-styled [[hatchback]].<ref>[https://www.motortrend.com/news/report-ford-fusion-name-will-live-on-as-wagon-like-crossover/]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/report-ford-fusion-to-live-on-as-a-subaru-outback-fighter|title=Report: Ford Fusion to Live On as a Subaru Outback Fighter|publisher=}}</ref> Ford itself would not comment on the Fusion's future.

On September 5, 2018, Ford ended all national and promotional advertising (including sales and special offers) for its entire sedan lineup, including the Fusion, whose production will continue despite its possible discontinuation.<ref>[http://www.autonews.com/article/20180905/RETAIL03/180909886/ford-stops-national-ads-for-sedans-including-fusion-still-in?X-IgnoreUserAgent=1 “Ford stops national ads for sedans, including Fusion still in production”] from Automotive News (September 5, 2018)</ref>

The performance-oriented Fusion Sport was discontinued after the 2019 model year. Ford plans to "focus on more popular styles" of the Fusion.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2019/06/04/ford-fusion-sport-discontinued-2020/</ref> Sightings of a prototype, based on the Focus wagon but enlarged, have raised speculation that the Fusion will live on as a crossover/wagon equivalent based on the next generation Mondeo, and will be repositioned to compete with the Outback. <ref>[https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30653717/ford-fusion-wagon-spied/ “Next Ford Fusion Takes Shape as a Subaru Outback–Style Lifted Wagon”] from Car & Driver (January 24, 2020)</ref>

The sedan version is expected to be discontinued after the 2021 model year, effectively ending what will be left of Ford’s car lineup in North America except for the Mustang.

==Auto racing==

===NASCAR===
[[File:Ricky Stenhouse, Jr., 2013 STP Gas Booster 500.JPG|thumb|The [[2013 NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|2013]] [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series|NASCAR Sprint Cup Series]] Generation 6 version of the Ford Fusion as driven by [[Ricky Stenhouse Jr.]] at [[Martinsville Speedway]].]]

The Fusion also became the new body style for Ford automobiles in [[NASCAR]] beginning in 2006, replacing the [[Ford Taurus|Taurus]].<ref name="Ford Racing: Ford Unveils New Face For The Chase">{{cite web|url=http://www.fordracing.com/news/detail/?article=28461|publisher=Fordracing.com|title=Ford Racing: Ford Unveils New Face For The Chase|accessdate=November 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929024816/http://www.fordracing.com/news/detail/?article=28461|archivedate=September 29, 2007}}</ref>  This marked the first time since the [[Ford Torino|Torino]] in 1968 that Ford introduced a new model that went racing in NASCAR at the same time as its launch.<ref name=yahoonascar>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-cottest&prov=ap&type=lgns |title=NASCAR may move COT to full schedule in 2008 |accessdate=March 1, 2007 |first=Jenna |last=Fryer |date=February 28, 2007 |agency=Associated Press |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308000142/http://sports.yahoo.com/nascar/news?slug=ap-nascar-cottest&prov=ap&type=lgns |archivedate=March 8, 2007 }}</ref>

For the introduction of the [[Generation 6 (NASCAR)|Generation 6]] body design in 2013, the vehicles were updated to match the second generation Fusion. The Generation 6 body styles were also meant to closer resemble the production versions of their respective vehicles.<ref name="autoblog-gen6">{{cite web|title=Ford debuts Fusion NASCAR racer that edges closer to stock [w/video]|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/02/20/ford-debuts-fusion-nascar-racer-that-edges-closer-to-stock-w-vi/|website=Autoblog|publisher=AOL|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name="ftu-gen6">{{cite web|title=NASCAR switches to uncommon look|url=http://jacksonville.com/sports/racing/2013-02-14/story/nascar-switches-uncommon-look|website=Florida Times-Union|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref>

On April 17, 2018, Ford announced that the [[Ford Mustang (sixth generation)|Mustang]] will replace the Fusion in the [[2019 Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2018/04/17/ford-mustang-monster-energy-series-in-2019/ |title=Ford Mustang planned for Monster Energy Series in 2019 |website=NASCAR.com |date=April 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/a19838299/ford-mustang-to-nascar-monster-energy-cup-2019/ |title=Ford Will Replace the Fusion With the Mustang in NASCAR |author=Silvestro, Brian |magazine=[[Road & Track]] |date=April 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref>

===Land speed record success===
Ford announced its attempt to use a fuel cell version of the Fusion, Ford Fusion Hydrogen 999, to set a land speed record on August 10–17 during Bonneville Speed Week in 2007.<ref name="Ford Fusion Hydrogen 999 Racer To Attempt Speed Record For Fuel Cell-Powered Vehicle">{{cite web|url=http://media.ford.com/newsroom/feature_display.cfm?release=25641|title=Ford Fusion Hydrogen 999 Racer To Attempt Speed Record For Fuel Cell-Powered Vehicle|accessdate=November 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029182139/http://media.ford.com/newsroom/feature_display.cfm?release=25641|archivedate=October 29, 2007}}</ref> The Fusion 999 project was born in early 2006 when Ford fuel cell engineering manager Mujeeb Ijaz approached [[Roush Racing]] about a project to demonstrate the performance potential of a fuel cell-powered vehicle.

Roush's team, led by Rick Darling, worked with a team of Ford engineers and technicians led by Matt Zuehlk to come up with a vehicle design that could meet the goal of exceeding {{convert|200|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} on the [[Bonneville Salt Flats]], fueled only by hydrogen.<ref name="AutblogGreen: Ford's Hydrogen Fusion 999 Hits The Track For The First Time">{{cite web| url= http://www.autobloggreen.com/2007/07/17/video-fords-hydrogen-fusion-999-hits-the-track-for-the-first-t/|title=AutblogGreen: Ford's Hydrogen Fusion 999 Hits The Track For The First Time| accessdate= November 18, 2007}}</ref> On August 15, 2007, the vehicle set the fastest fuel cell ground vehicle speed record of {{convert|207.297|mi/h|km/h|3|abbr=on}}.

The car was driven by retired Ford engineer Rick Byrnes, a long time [[Bonneville Speedway|Bonneville racer]].<ref name="AutoblogGreen: Ford Hydrogen Fusion 999 runs 207.3 MPH at Bonneville">{{cite web|url=http://www.autobloggreen.com/2007/08/16/ford-hydrogen-fusion-999-runs-207-3-mph-at-bonneville/|title=AutoblogGreen: Ford Hydrogen Fusion 999 runs 207.3 MPH at Bonneville|accessdate=November 18, 2007}}</ref>

