{{other uses|Ford GT (disambiguation)}}{{Update|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox automobile | name = Galpin GTR1 | image = Galpin GTR1.JPG | image_size = | caption = Galpin GTR1 at the 2013 [[LA Auto Show]] | manufacturer = [[Galpin Auto Sports]] | production = 2013–present | assembly = [[California]] | body_style = 2-door [[coupe]] | class = Sports car ([[S-segment|S]]) | related = [[Ford GT]] | layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|RMR layout]] | engine = 5.4L twin-[[turbocharged]] [[V8 engine|V8]] | transmission = 6-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] | length = | predecessor = | also called = Galpin Ford GTR1 }}
The '''Galpin GTR1''' (sometimes referred to as the '''Galpin Ford GTR1''') is a custom sports car based on the [[Ford GT]] developed and built by American automotive company [[Galpin Auto Sports]]. The car was unveiled at [[Pebble Beach]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahrens|first=Ronald|title=Pebble Beach Weekend: Galpin Unveils 1,024-Horsepower Ford GTR1|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/19/pebble-beach-weekend-galpin-unveils-1024-horsepower-ford-gtr1/?_r=1|accessdate=September 2, 2013|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 19, 2013}}</ref> Galpin plans to make at least six cars in 2014, with the possibility of another 18 to follow, based on demand.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/08/16/galpin-ford-gtr1-supercar-monterey-2013/ |title=Galpin Ford GTR1 supercar debuts in Monterey |publisher=Autoblog |date=16 August 2013 |first=Brandon |last=Turkus}}</ref>
==Specifications== In 2013, [[Galpin Auto Sports]] utilized the mechanical underpinnings of a Ford GT as basis to build the GTR1. The GTR1 has a 5.4L twin-turbocharged V8, capable of producing {{convert|1024|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|739|lb·ft|N·m|0|abbr=on}} of torque, which enables the car to accelerate from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in about 3 seconds, and reach an advertised top speed of {{convert|225|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name="autocar">{{cite web |url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/pebble-beach/galpin-gtr1-unveiled-pebble-beach |title=Galpin GTR1 unveiled at Pebble Beach |publisher=Autocar |date=17 August 2013 |accessdate=21 September 2013 |first=Jim |last=Holder}}</ref> However, if the GTR1 is fuelled with 100-octane fuel, the power and torque outputs are boosted to respectively {{convert|1197|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|887|lb·ft|N·m|0|abbr=on}} of torque.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.windingroad.com/articles/reviews/preview-galpin-ford-gtr1/ |title=Preview: Galpin Ford GTR1 |publisher=Winding Road |date=19 August 2013 |accessdate=21 September 2013 |first=John Beltz |last=Snyder}}</ref> The hand-built, all-aluminum chassis features carbon fiber detailing, and LED headlights,<ref name="autocar"/> and is approximately {{convert|5|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} wider than the standard Ford GT.<ref name="carscoops"/> The interior is only slightly altered from the Ford GT, but now has leather upholstery, a machined aluminum instrument cluster, and a [[McIntosh Laboratory|McIntosh]] audio system.<ref name="wcf">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/113081761569/galpin-gtr1-prototype-unveiled-at-pebble-beach |title=Galpin GTR1 prototype unveiled at Pebble Beach |publisher=World Car Fans |date=17 August 2013 |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref> The GTR1 uses 20" aluminum wheels, which are fitted with [[Pirelli]] P-Zero tires.<ref name="wcf"/> Carbon fiber [[disc brake]]s, with six-piston calipers and [[Reinforced carbon–carbon]] rotors are used to stop the car. It is the only car in the world, besides [[Formula One]] cars, to have carbon-carbon rotors.<ref name="carscoops">{{cite web |url=http://www.carscoops.com/2013/08/1024hp-galpin-gtr1-is-what-modern-day.html |title=1,024HP Galpin GTR1 is what a Modern Day Ford GT Could Have Looked Like [w/Videos] |publisher=Carscoops |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=21 September 2013 |first=Dan |last=Mihalascu}}</ref>
