{{Infobox weapon |name=Ford Pygmy |image=Ford Pygmy jeep pilot vehicle.JPG |image_size=280px |caption=Ford Pygmy at U.S. Veterans Memorial Museum |origin= United States |type={{frac|1|4}} ton (227kg){{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=rating|Off-road load rating.}} 4×4 utility truck <!-- Type selection --> |is_vehicle=yes |is_UK= <!-- Service history --> |service= |used_by= |wars= <!-- Production history --> |designer= |design_date= |manufacturer=[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] |production_date=23 November 1940 |number= 1 |variants= <!-- General specifications --> |spec_label=Pygmy |weight={{convert|2,100|lb|abbr=on}} road |length= {{convert|133|in|m|2|abbr=on}} |width= {{convert|59|in|m|2|abbr=on}} overall |height= {{convert|59|in|m|2|abbr=on}} |crew= 3 <!-- Vehicle specifications --> |armour= |primary_armament= |secondary_armament= |engine=119.5 CID, 4 cyl, side valve (Fordson Model N tractor engine) |engine_power={{convert|45|bhp|kW|abbr=on}} @ 3,600 rpm |suspension=Beam axles on leaf springs |vehicle_range= |speed= }}
The '''Ford Pygmy''' is the pilot vehicle submitted by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] in response to the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]'s requirement for a "light reconnaissance and command car" during the military buildup prior to [[World War II]], which later became better known as the [[Willys MB|World War II jeep]].
The Pygmy is the only known survivor of the original pilot vehicles tested by the Army.
== History == [[File:Pygmy01.jpg|left|thumb|Ford Pygmy during testing at Camp Holabird, Maryland]] [[American Austin Car Company|American Bantam]] was the first to deliver a pilot vehicle to the Army on 23 September 1940. [[Willys-Overland]] followed with its Quad on 13 November. On 23 November,<ref>ARMY MOTORS (1991, Summer). Editor's note. ARMY MOTORS #57, 8.</ref> [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] delivered two pilot vehicles to [[Fort Holabird|Camp Holabird]], Maryland for testing: the Pygmy and a second vehicle with a body built by the [[Budd Company]]. The Budd-bodied vehicle more closely resembled the Bantam pilot and was not tested by the Army. Both the Willys and Ford vehicles were heavily based on the Bantam Pilot design.
The Pygmy was hand-built in the Ford development shop in Dearborn, Michigan using parts from Ford's commercial and agricultural lines. It was the first of the pilot vehicles to feature a flat grill with headlamps positioned behind it for protection, an intermediate bow for the canvas top, its fuel tank mounted inside the body under the driver’s seat, and a two‐piece opening/folding windshield with a round tubing frame. Another innovation was headlamps positioned on hinged brackets which allowed them to be pivoted to illuminate the engine compartment at night. All of these design features were ultimately incorporated into the standard World War II [[Jeep#Origin of the name|jeep]], the {{nowrap|[[Willys MB]].}}
The pilot vehicles were the property of the manufacturer and after testing was complete, the army returned them. The Pygmy was donated to the [[Henry Ford Museum]] by [[Henry Ford II]] in 1948. It was acquired at auction by a private collector in 1982,<ref>Withrow, Randall. "PYGMY The Saga Continues." ARMY MOTORS #53 Summer 1990: 16-17. Print.</ref> and is now in the collection of [http://www.memorialmuseum.org The U.S. Veterans Memorial Museum] in Huntsville, Alabama where it is preserved in virtually original un-restored condition. [[File:Pygmy accession sheet.pdf|thumb|left|Ford Pygmy Accession Sheet]]
The second Ford pilot was discovered in 1998 derelict in a field in California. It was obtained by a private collector in the United Kingdom and has been restored. Neither the original Bantam Pilot nor the Willys Quad are known to have survived. The oldest (and only) known surviving Bantam BRC‐60, serial number 1007, belongs to the [[Smithsonian Institution]] and is currently displayed at the [[Heinz History Center]] in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. It was delivered to the Army 29 November 1940, six days after the Pygmy arrived at Camp Holabird for testing. [[File:Bantam 1007 data plate.png|right|thumb|Bantam S/N 1007 data plate]]
