{{Infobox automobile | name =El Matador | image = | caption = | manufacturer = [[Bill Cushenberry]] | aka = | production = 1959-61 | model_years = | assembly = | designer = | class = | body_style = | layout = | platform = | related = | engine = | transmission = | propulsion = | wheelbase = | length = | width = | height = | weight = | predecessor = | successor = | sp = us }} '''''El Matador''''' is a [[custom car]] built by [[Bill Cushenberry]] during 1959–1961. It was his first show car.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}}
Cushenberry began work on ''El Matador'' in late 1959 as a showcase for his talents and a rolling advertisement.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}} It started as a 1939 Ford,{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}} [[Custom car#Language|chopped]] {{convert|4+1/2|in|mm|abbr=on}} and [[Customcar#Language|sectioned]] {{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=85}} '57 Olds parking lights were used as taillights.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=85}} The nerf bar bumpers were adapted from upper bumper rails off a 1950 Pontiac.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=85}}
He scrounged parts from Seaside Auto Wreckers, operated by Vick Irvan (father of [[Ernie Irvan]]).{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}} The rear window was a windshield from a 1951 Chevrolet fastback, mounted upside-down.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}}
The car featured vertically-stacked, inward-canted headlights{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=84}} (a common customizing idea at the time), with hand-formed steel front end and chrome mesh grille.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=84}}
''El Matador'' debuted in February 1961 at the [[Oakland Roadster Show]].{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}}
Cushenberry sold the car to Bob Larivee, Sr.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}}
''El Matador'' and [[Exodus (custom car)|''Exodus'']], which appeared the same year, drew a lot of attention to Cushenberry and a lot of custom work for his shop.{{sfn|Rod & Custom|p=83}}
