{{Infobox automobile | name =0032 | image = | caption = | manufacturer = Ford | aka = | production = | model_years =1932 | assembly = | designer =Chip Foose | class = | body_style = Roadster | layout = | platform = | related = | engine = | transmission = | propulsion = | wheelbase = | length = | width = | height = | weight = | predecessor = | successor = | sp = uk }}
'''''0032''''' is a [[Custom car|custom]]-built [[1932 Ford]] [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]] built by [[Chip Foose]] for Chuck Svatos. It won the 2000 [[America's Most Beautiful Roadster]] award.
== History == ''0032'' started life as a [[Hot Rods by Boyd]] project, [[Boydster II (custom car)|''Boydster II'']]. After Hot Rods by Boyd went [[bankruptcy|bankrupt]], the car was taken in hand by Foose. It was repainted black, over the original yellow, reupholstered, and entered in the [[2000 Oakland Roadster Show|2000]] [[Grand National Roadster Show|Oakland Roadster Show]]. It won that year's America's Most Beautiful Roadster award.<ref>Geisert, Eric. "Ron Whiteside's Ridler Winner", in ''Street Rodder'', July 2003, p.80.</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= Aguilar |first= Kevin |title= Exclusive Chip Foose Interview |work= Sport Truck |date= April 3, 2006 |url= http://www.sporttruck.com/0605st_chip_foose_interview/ |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070126062314/http://www.sporttruck.com/0605st_chip_foose_interview/ |archivedate= January 26, 2007 |df= mdy-all }}</ref><ref>[https://www.rodshows.com/gnrs/show-history.html Oakland Roadster Show winners] (retrieved 15 November 2018)</ref>
As built, the car rode on a set of Foose's custom-designed five-spoke knockoff wheels, one of only two sets to exist (the other used on his [[Detroit Autorama|Ridler]]-winner, [[The Stallion (custom car)|''The Stallion'']]), as [[Hot rod#Language|"big'n'little"]]s: {{convert|7|x|16|in|cm|abbr=on}} in front, {{convert|8|x|17|in|cm|abbr=on}} in back.<ref>Geisert, Eric. "Ron Whiteside's Ridler Winner", in ''Street Rodder'', July 2003, p.81.</ref>
''0032'' was Foose's first project as an independent operator.<ref>Geisert, Eric. "Ron Whiteside's Ridler Winner", in ''Street Rodder'', July 2003, p.80.</ref>
