'''USCGC ''Earp'' (ex-Eagle 22)''' was a {{convert|200|ft|m|0|adj=on}} US Coast Guard anti-submarine [[Eagle-class patrol craft|''Eagle''-class vessel]] built by [[Ford Motor Co.]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]. ''Earp'' was designed for quick construction and was one of 100 ordered. ''Earp'' was launched on 5 August 1918 and commissioned on 17 July 1919 by the [[United States Navy]] and again on 17 March 1920 by the [[United States Coast Guard]]. She was named by the Coast Guard for Ensign James Marsden Earp,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.history.uscg.mil/tampa/ |title=''Tampa'' (ex-''Miami'') |website=U.S. Coast Guard Historian's Office |accessdate=2019-07-19}}</ref> a crewmember killed in the September 1918 U-boat sinking of [[USCGC Tampa (1912)|USCGC ''Tampa'']]. ''Earp'' was decommissioned on 22 May 1923.
[[File:US Coast Guard Cutter Earp - Entire Crew.JPG|300px|thumbnail|left|Complete crew of USCGC Earp - 1921]]
