{{one source|date=November 2018}}
'''''The Stallion'''''  is a [[Custom car|custom]]ized [[1932 Ford|1934 Ford]] [[Coupé#Three window coupe|3-window]] built by [[Chip Foose]] for Ron Whiteside. It won the Ridler Award at the 2003 [[Detroit Autorama]].

== Construction details ==
The chassis is custom-made by [[Larry Sergeff]], with a {{convert|114|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[wheelbase]], {{convert|2|in|mm|abbr=on}} more than stock.{{sfn|Geisert}}

Andy Wallin built the engine, starting with a 1996 {{convert|350|cid|cc|abbr=on}} [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|Corvette]] [[Chevrolet small-block engine#LT4|LT4]] [[crate engine]], with stainless steel [[Exhaust manifold|headers]], built by [[Steve Greninger]], and mufflers from Stainless Steel Specialties.{{sfn|Geisert}} Greninger custom-built a cover for the [[fuel injection]], and Karl Jonasson machined custom [[valve cover]]s.{{sfn|Geisert}} It is mated to a [[Turbo-Hydramatic#THM700R4 / 4L60 / 4L60E / 4L65E / 4L70E|TH700-R4]] [[automatic transmission]], controlled by a 1998 Camaro shifter,{{sfn|Geisert}} connected to rear axle (ratio 3.55:1) by an aluminum driveshaft provided by Empire Driveline.{{sfn|Geisert}} The Jack Mattson radiator uses a [[Vintage Air]] fan.{{sfn|Geisert}} The [[alternator (automotive)|alternator]] is a 100 [[Ampere|amp]] Powermaster.{{sfn|Geisert}}

The [[Independent suspension#$RS|IRS]], based on a late-model Corvette, was carved from [[billet (semi-finished product)|billet]] aluminum by Larry Sergeff, who also did the IFS.{{sfn|Geisert}} The [[shock absorber]]s are [[Carrera (company)|Carrera]] coilovers, the brakes in [[Wilwood]] [[disc brake|disc]]s, mated to a [[master cylinder]] from a 1994 Corvette.{{sfn|Geisert}} The [[steering box]] is from a [[Fiat Automobiles|Fiat]].{{sfn|Geisert}} The car rides on a set of Foose's custom-designed polished five-spoke Nitrous Thrust knockoff wheels, one of only two sets to exist (the other used on his [[America's Most Beautiful Roadster|AMBR]]-winner, [[0032 (custom car)|''0032'']]), as [[Hot rod#Language|"big'n'little"]]s:  {{convert|7|x|16|in|cm|abbr=on}} in front, {{convert|8|x|17|in|cm|abbr=on}} in back, with Nitto tires (195/50 front, 255/50 rear0).{{sfn|Geisert}}

The coupé's body is all steel (the hood sides aluminum).{{sfn|Geisert}} It has been slant-[[Chopping and channeling#Chopping|chopped]] {{convert|3|in|cm|abbr=on}} (measured at the windshield posts) and pie-[[Sectioning (automobile)|sectioned]] {{convert|4|in|cm|abbr=on}} (measured at the front fenders), then fitting hidden hinges on the doors, which were lengthened {{convert|2|in|cm|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Geisert}}
The door mirrors and door handles were shaved, as were all the badges.{{sfn|Geisert}} The stainless steel grille, designed by Foose, was fabricated by Don Fink Metalworks.{{sfn|Geisert}}

[[Jim Griffin (customizer)|Jim Griffin]], who also did [[Grand Master (custom car)|''Grand Master'']], [[Snyper (custom car)|''Snyper'']], and the [[Smoothster (custom car)|''Smoothster'']], built and upholstered ''The Stallion''; assisted by his son, James,{{sfn|Geisert}} he fabricated seats and covered them in two shades of tan leather, while the [[Headliner (material)|headliner]] is [[suede]].{{sfn|Geisert}} The steering wheel is an{{convert|18|in|cm|abbr=on}} piece from a 1950 [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]], resized to {{convert|14|in|cm|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Geisert}} The [[Panasonic]] [[DVD player]] hides behind a Red Mountain Audio head unit.{{sfn|Geisert}} The dash had an aluminum insert, containing [[Classic Instruments]] gauges, while the interior rear view mirror came from [[Billet Specialties]].{{sfn|Geisert}} The [[air conditioning]] system was supplied by Vintage Air.{{sfn|Geisert}}

The exterior was painted in [[Glasurit]]'s Sedona Fire paint by [[Chris Guinn]], with final [[pin striping|striping]] by [[Dennis Ricklefs]].{{sfn|Geisert}}

Foose used Mercury badging throughout, saying the coupé was the kind of car Mercury would have built, had the [[marque]] existed at the time.{{sfn|Geisert}}

== History ==
Whiteside purchased the car in 1965 for US$150.{{sfn|Geisert}} It took the better part of two years for Whiteside to get the car road-worthy, before being forced to leave it the hands of his younger brothers, Randy and Steve, when he was [[Conscription in the United States|drafted]].{{sfn|Geisert}} The brothers [[Drag racing|drag raced]] the car; when Whiteside returned, he joined them, and the car was raced during 1972-75.{{sfn|Geisert}}

After that, Whiteside parked the car until 1986, when he began rebuilding it, with the aid of Ken Garman and Don Maki (who later went to work with Foose).{{sfn|Geisert}} Over the course of two years, the car was rebuilt.

During this process, Whiteside showed photographs of the project to [[Boyd Coddington]], hoping his shop (Hot Rods by Boyd) could build a [[Detroit Autorama#Past winners|Ridler Award]] winner.{{sfn|Geisert}} It was through Coddington's shop Foose conceived a sister car, a [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]], which ultimately became [[Impact (custom car)|''Impact'']], after the [[bankruptcy]] of Coddington's [[Boyds Wheels]], and the consequent failure of his rod shop.{{sfn|Geisert}}

Foose took over the project, working out of his [[Orange, California|Orange]] and later [[Huntington Beach, California|Huntington Beach]] premises, aided by [[Roy Schmidt (customizer)|Roy Schmidt]], Brian Fuller, [[Marcel DeLay]] (and his sons, Marc and Luc), Dennis Graff, Chris Guinn, Don Maki, Paco Castell, Chris Eddie, Tom Marcotte, Lance Nabors, Larry Sergeff, and Steve Greninger (many of them former Coddington employees).{{sfn|Geisert}}

The car was completed in 2003, in time for the Autorama; Whiteside won the Ridler.{{sfn|Geisert}}

Unlike many show-quality customs, this car is actually driven.{{sfn|Geisert}}

